EXAMPLE OF THIS IS C++ . 


5.Explain thr difference between interpretation vs compilation and how is the performance different .
Ans5. Compiled language -->It follows at least two levels to get from source code to execution. 
       #A compiled language is converted into machine code so that the processor can execute it.
       #In a compiled language, the code can be executed by the CPU.
	
Interpreted language --> It follows one step to get from source code to execution.
	#The interpreted programs run slower than the compiled program.
	#In this languages, the program cannot be compiled, it is interpreted.
	#This language delivers slower performance.

6.What is backward compatibility and does java support this feature.
Ans6. Backward compatibility in java is a property which allows older API usages to function without breaking their existing implenetations when API is modified . Yes Java support this.

7. State the difference between float and double.
Ans7.The main difference between float and double 
      #Size :- Float is of size 32 bits while double is of size 64 bits.
      #Precision :- Float can allow only 7 bits of precision ,But double allow almost double the nuber of bits for the exponent
      #Wrapper Class :- Both float abd double are primitive types . This means these are having there own Wrapper class .The wrapper class for the float is java.lang.Float
                        while the Wrapper class for the double is java.lang.Double .  

